		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/05/03/opinion/tg-lede-LN/tg-lede-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/05/03/opinion/tg-lede-LN/tg-lede-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/05/03/opinion/tg-lede-LN/tg-lede-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000003865570" width="592" height="425" alt="Transgender issues were among the most popular news topics chosen by students for our 2015 Summer Reading Contest. &lt;a href=&quot;//www.nytimes.com/2015/05/04/opinion/the-quest-for-transgender-equality.html&quot;&gt;Related Series&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a&gt;&lt;/a&gt;"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="425"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Transgender issues were among the most popular news topics chosen by students for our 2015 Summer Reading Contest. <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/05/04/opinion/the-quest-for-transgender-equality.html">Related Series</a><br /><a></a></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Damon Winter/The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/08/21/three-ways-to-encourage-your-students-to-follow-current-events-this-school-year/" data-title="Three Teacher-Tested Ways to Encourage Your Students to Follow Current Events This School Year" data-description="The Summer Reading Contest is now over, but here are some teacher-tested ideas for bringing its spirit into your classroom this fall, no matter how much time you have to give to current events.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><webonly><span id="t10h0s" class="update">Updated, Aug. 24 | </span></webonly></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Over 7,500 mini-essays answering the question &#8220;What interested you most in The Times this week?&#8221; flooded into our <a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/05/07/the-sixth-annual-new-york-times-summer-reading-contest/">Sixth Annual Summer Reading Contest</a> this June, July and August, and so far we have crowned <a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/tag/summer-reading-winner/">eight winners</a>, 79 runners-up and many, many honorable mentions. (And stay tuned: There are still winners to be named on Aug. 25 and Sept. 1., as well a <a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/08/24/the-learning-network-student-council-an-opportunity-for-students-honored-in-our-summer-reading-contest/">special opportunity for honorees.</a>)</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Just as we have every summer since 2010, we found that offering students free choice to read whatever <em>they</em> liked best resulted in a surprising breadth of topics. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Among the most popular: transgender rights; Cecil the lion; the Greek economy; beauty standards; space travel; Donald Trump; ISIS; &#8220;Go Set a Watchman&#8221;; the pressure on teenagers to succeed; criminal justice reform; race and identity; the migrant crisis in Europe; the Common Core; living in a connected world; robots; baseball; the Confederate flag; and the Women&#8217;s World Cup. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Below, some teacher-tested ideas for bringing the spirit of our Summer Reading Contest into the classroom this fall, no matter how much time you have to give to current events.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="more-160233"></span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">First, though, to help sell you on the notion, an unsolicited email that recently made our day (month?) when it arrived from a student participant, Rocel Beatriz S. Balmes:</p>
<blockquote><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I just wanted you (and the staff who makes all of this possible) to know that this Summer Reading Contest has had such a huge impact on me. As an aspiring author and rising senior with several drafts of college application essays open, I&#8217;ve finally found a topic that will actually convey who I am and who I want to be: journalism! I&#8217;ve always found writing and the very concept of language incredibly freeing, but I didn&#8217;t realize the role that it played in shaping societal norms, versions of reality, and the ideologies of the masses until I subscribed to NYT on Facebook for this contest. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Though I didn&#8217;t participate in every week the contest was held, I did find myself reading at least four articles a day from the NYT ranging in topic from racial inequality to the best pasta recipe I&#8217;ve ever tried! Truly, this has been an eye-opening experience, and I cannot thank you enough for having this weekly contest and allowing young voices (which are too often silenced or disregarded as inexperienced and ignorant) a chance to speak on an international platform. If you ever decide to invite student submissions to NYT again, just know that you&#8217;ve made a loyal reader and writer out of me (and countless others, I&#8217;m sure). </p>
</blockquote>
<hr/>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/09/08/learning/50WaysCurrentEventsLN-copy/50WaysCurrentEventsLN-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/09/08/learning/50WaysCurrentEventsLN-copy/50WaysCurrentEventsLN-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/09/08/learning/50WaysCurrentEventsLN-copy/50WaysCurrentEventsLN-blog480.jpg" id="100000003865540" width="480" height="320" alt="Visit our related post,&lt;a href=&quot;//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/10/07/50-ways-to-teach-current-events/&quot;&gt; 50 Ways to Teach With Current Events&lt;/a&gt;."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="320"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Visit our related post,<a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/10/07/50-ways-to-teach-current-events/"> 50 Ways to Teach With Current Events</a>.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> The New York Times, left; Chip Somodevilla/Getty Images; and Jose Luis Magana/Associated Press</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Three Ways to Encourage Your Students to Follow Current Events This School Year</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>1. Set Aside &#8216;Nonfiction Fridays&#8217; for Student-Run Article Discussions</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Every week this summer we received scores of contest entries from students with the word &#8220;Huskie&#8221; appended to their names. We thought that must be the school mascot, until we received an email from Andie Huskie, their teacher. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">We love how she describes her classroom tradition of &#8220;Nonfiction Fridays&#8221; &#8212; what she calls &#8220;the highlight of our week&#8221;:</p>
<blockquote><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This is my third year teaching with the NYT Summer Reading Contest. I teach 11th grade English at <a href="//www.lcsd.k12.ny.us/lhs">Lansing High School</a> just north of Ithaca. Students in my honors classes are asked to submit three responses at any point during the summer as part of their summer reading assignment. (They&#8217;re also reading &#8220;Grapes of Wrath.&#8221;)</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Throughout the year we also hold &#8220;Nonfiction Friday&#8221; discussions each week, and they&#8217;ve been one of the most successful components of our curriculum. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Each week a different student brings in an article he or she is interested in and believes will be a good spark for class discussion. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On Monday, the student and I discuss questions he or she will pose to the class. On Tuesday, we pass out the article to the rest of the class. Students have until Friday to read, annotate and respond to the article in a one page mini-essay. They come in Friday ready to talk, and the student who chose the article moderates the discussion.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This practice really allows for student voices to dominate the classroom discussion. A lot of teachers worry about relinquishing control over discussion or the direction that the conversation might take. It certainly takes a willingness to be flexible and somewhat open, but students find the process empowering, challenging and essential to their growth as high school students preparing to take their first steps into college seminar-style classroom work. The practice has made Fridays the highlight of our week.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Last year we tackled lots of articles on the college admissions process, Internet and cell-phone privacy, space exploration, paying college athletes, campus rape and consent, &#8220;stand your ground&#8221; laws and police brutality. As you can imagine, often the best conversations were the toughest ones.</p>
</blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Need even more inspiration? A few years ago, two teachers in New Jersey went even further and began class each day by reading The New York Times. They <a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/06/05/it-opens-your-mind-a-student-made-video-about-a-year-of-reading-the-times/">blogged for us about the results</a>, and their students made this video:</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> <iframe width="480" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9zmKMGWEKPU" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen="yes"></iframe></p>
<hr/>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>2. Assign a Teacher-Chosen &#8216;Article of the Week&#8217; to Enrich Background Knowledge </strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This is an idea made popular by Kelly Gallagher, a literacy specialist and teacher, and adopted by teachers and school districts across the country. As <a href="//www.kellygallagher.org/article-of-the-week/">his Website explains</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Kelly recognizes that part of the reason his students struggle with reading is because they lack prior knowledge and background. They can decode the words, but the words remain meaningless without a foundation of knowledge. To help build his studentsâ prior knowledge, he assigns them an Article of the Week every Monday morning.</p></blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Gallagher has an <a href="//www.kellygallagher.org/aow-archive">archive</a> of articles that have worked for his students, and other teacher-writers like  <a href="//www.davestuartjr.com/article-of-the-week-assignment/">Dave Stuart Jr.</a> and <a href="//carriedeahl.typepad.com/the-real-deahl/2012/10/adoption-of-article-of-the-week-.html">Carrie Deahl</a> have detailed ways they have adapted his model. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Nancy Dandurand, an English teacher at <a href="//www.cumberlandschools.org/content/cumberland-high-school">Cumberland High School</a> in Rhode Island, assigned our contest this summer, and says she did so for much the same reason Mr. Gallagher chooses his Article of the Week:</p>
<blockquote><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I have two classes of AP Language and Composition.  Over the years, I&#8217;ve found the students to be woefully under-informed about the world around them.  Not only are my students reading and writing throughout five weeks [of your Summer Reading Contest], but they may become more informed about current ideas and events &#8212; besides what they get only through social media.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I would like to incorporate continuing the responses in my classes. For the AP Language and Composition Argument essay, the students need to draw on their own knowledge. I&#8217;m hoping this exercise strengthens that. </p></blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Whether you choose to have students write an open-ended reflection, keep a <a href="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs/learning/pdf/activities/ReadingLog_NYTLN.pdf">reading log</a>, practice <a href="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs/learning/pdf/2013/13-1553_K12_Double-Entry_LearnNet_RP3-f.pdf">close-reading</a>, or do <a href="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs/learning/pdf/activities/OnePager_NYTLN.pdf">something more artistic</a> with your Article of the Week assignment, we&#8217;d love to <a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/great-ideas-from-our-readers/">hear from you</a> if you choose a piece from The New York Times.</p>
<hr/>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/14/arts/14CAROUSELJP2-LN/14CAROUSELJP2-blog480-v2.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/14/arts/14CAROUSELJP2-LN/14CAROUSELJP2-blog480-v2.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/14/arts/14CAROUSELJP2-LN/14CAROUSELJP2-blog480-v2.jpg" id="100000003865342" width="480" height="320" alt="Many students in the final week of our Summer Reading Contest wrote about a piece onÂ &lt;a href=&quot;//www.nytimes.com/2015/08/14/arts/design/new-yorks-new-carousel-puts-you-in-a-whirling-school-of-mechanized-fish.html&quot;&gt;New York&#039;s new carousel&lt;/a&gt;, which features translucent fiberglass fish that shimmer and glow from within."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="320"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Many students in the final week of our Summer Reading Contest wrote about a piece onÂ <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/08/14/arts/design/new-yorks-new-carousel-puts-you-in-a-whirling-school-of-mechanized-fish.html">New York's new carousel</a>, which features translucent fiberglass fish that shimmer and glow from within.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Karsten Moran for The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<hr/>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>3. Host a One-Time Current Events <a href="https://www.facinghistory.org/for-educators/educator-resources/teaching-strategies/gallery-walk-teaching-strateg">Gallery Walk</a> (Live or Virtual) Each Semester</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">If you participated in this summer&#8217;s contest, you might start the semester by inviting your students to host a &#8220;show and tell,&#8221; either live or online, about what they read this summer and why. If you didn&#8217;t, you could choose a date later in the semester and invite students to share what they&#8217;ve been reading then.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Here are some ideas:</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; Invite each student to bring in text, photos and/or graphics related to the news story that most interested them and <a href="https://www.facinghistory.org/for-educators/educator-resources/teaching-strategies/gallery-walk-teaching-strateg">post them on your classroom wall</a>. Or, if you&#8217;d rather do this virtually, invite them to post their picks on your classroom website or blog. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; Next, have students circulate around the room, or scroll through your site, commenting on at least three of the pieces by leaving notes next to them. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; Finally, have a whole-class discussion, live or online, about what students noticed. What pieces stood out? Why? What commonalities did they notice in the choices? Which stories were new to them, and which had they already known about? Which would they like to learn more about? Why?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; For a final project, you might invite students to choose one of the pieces someone else in the class brought in and learn more about it, then fill out our activity sheet, <a href="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs/learning/pdf/activities/ConnectWorld_NYTLN.pdf">Connecting The New York Times to Your World </a> (PDF), to make &#8220;text to text,&#8221; &#8220;text to self&#8221; and &#8220;text to world&#8221; connections.</p>
<hr/>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Want even more ideas? Our<a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/10/07/50-ways-to-teach-current-events/"> 50 Ways to Teach With Current Events</a> can help you out &#8212; and don&#8217;t forget that, starting Aug. 24, we&#8217;ll be asking a <a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/category/student-opinion/">Student Opinion question</a> every day this school year, on which any teenager anywhere in the world is invited to comment. Here are the <a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/06/10/183-questions-for-writing-or-discussion/">183 we asked in the 2014-15 school year,</a> all still open to response.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><webonly><span id="t11h24s" class="update">Updated, Aug. 23 | </span></webonly> A reader wrote in this week to ask:</p>
<blockquote><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Do students need to have a paid subscription to access the Times all year, more than the allotted 10 times per month? Are there student rates? All school rates? Ways that schools can make everyday access more affordable for all students, not just the ones whose parents will pay for a subscription?</p></blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Great questions! First, The Learning Network is <a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/03/17/a-note-to-our-readers-about-digital-subscriptions/">free and accessible without a digital subscription</a>, as is everything in The Times we link to.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Anyone with an iPhone can also access <a href="//www.nytimes.com/nytnow/">NYTNow</a> for free.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As for student, teacher and school-wide subscriptions, <a href="//nytimesinschool.com/digital-subscriptions-qa/">this page</a> should explain all the options. </p>
	</div>
